<p class="">    <h2>Key Challenges in the Radioisotopes Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Supply Chain Limitations:</strong> The production of radioisotopes is often hampered by complexities in the supply chain, including stringent regulatory requirements and the dependence on aging nuclear infrastructure. This leads to potential shortages and impacts the timely availability of critical isotopes.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Regulatory Hurdles:</strong> Navigating the landscape of regulations surrounding the use and distribution of radioisotopes is a significant challenge. Compliance with safety standards can slow down the introduction of new products and technologies.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Technological Constraints:</strong> Limited technological advancements in the production processes can lead to inefficiencies. Many production methods are outdated, resulting in high costs and potential reliability issues in isotope supply.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Public Perception:</strong> The stigma associated with nuclear materials poses a barrier. Misinformation can lead to public resistance against nuclear medicine, impacting investment and innovation in the field.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Cost Issues:</strong> The high cost of producing and sourcing radioisotopes can deter smaller organizations from entering the market. As healthcare budgets become tighter globally, competitive pricing becomes essential.        </li>    </ul>    <h2>Potential Growth Opportunities</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Advancements in Production Technology:</strong> Innovations in production techniques, such as the development of non-uranium sources and more efficient reactors, present an opportunity to enhance yield and reduce costs.         </li>        <li>            <strong>Emerging Applications:</strong> The growing use of radioisotopes in targeted alpha therapy and personalized medicine 